NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to the play. This is a hard hand. But the best bet is to probably try and set up clubs before losing control of the hand. So, play ace of clubs and a club. Then play ace of hearts and heart to the board, ruff another club. Then you end up losing just 1 heart, 1 spade, and 1 diamond. That technique, where you set up dummy, is known as a "dummy reversal."|
PG| ***** 96 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Psychologically, setting up dummy is harder to see than setting up your hand. I have done experiments where I have students play the same hand out, but switch which hand is declarer. Inevitably, on hands like these, if east had been declarer, the hand is better played than when west is declarer. Interesting psychology, for some reason, setting up dummy is harder to visualize.|
